  "prompt": "Which is more acidic phenol or paranitro phenol?",
  "response": "**p-Nitrophenol** is more acidic than **phenol**. This is due to the presence of the electron-withdrawing nitro group (\u2212NO\u2082) attached to the phenol ring at the para position. \n\n### Explanation:\n1. **Electron-withdrawing effect of the nitro group**: The \u2212NO\u2082 group withdraws electron density from the phenolic ring through both inductive and resonance effects. This stabilizes the phenoxide ion (the conjugate base formed after losing a proton) by delocalizing the negative charge.\n\n2. **Increased acidity**: The stabilization of the phenoxide ion makes it easier for p-nitrophenol to lose a proton, increasing its acidity compared to phenol.\n\nThus, **p-nitrophenol** is significantly more acidic than phenol.",
